inn1.comm: right on the money and it's firmly defended
smack! Just short of a length, but it's too wide and McCullum flays it over extra cover for a huge six
better line outside off and it's left alone
on his leg stump and oh no! Oh dear oh dear, what a complete shambles from Anderson at fine leg. He ran in and was foxed by the spin, the ball fizzing past him. Hilarity
close! Trapped in the crease, it nipped back but didn't come back quite enough
big step down the pitch and he flicks it, Pietersen-style, down to Anderson at fine leg who, this time, fields it cleanly
hit back to the bowler
wide of the off stump and smashed to cover
and he shoulders arms to this wider delivery
that's a good line from Anderson, right in the channel and it's defended off the back foot by Astle
ooh very well bowled, Anderson, cutting this back into Astle who defends
flicked to midwicket and a quick single there
too wide of his off stump
oh dear, too wide and it's hammered on the up through extra cover for four
good length, defended solidly
again this cuts back and again it's well blocked out
firmly clunked back to the bowler
turned with a closed face of the bat but no run on offer there
far too wide. Far, far too wide and he is very lucky not to be smashed for four. As it is, the batsman got a bottom edge trying to slash it over the slips
ooh lovely ball this time, in the channel and it zings past a very wishy washy backward defence
a swing and a miss outside off
cut hard into the covers
excellent bowling; just short of a length and it cuts back into the batsman who is cramped for room
gorgeous shot, quite effortless. Drifting down the leg side and he just flicks it down to fine leg for four. Easy.
good line from Lewis, Astle gets a thick inside edge onto his pad
more good lines from Lewis, just outside off and cutting back; Astle looks a touch clueless here to the moving ball
but this one doesn't move...in fact, the only thing that moved were Astle's feet and his bat, smacking this over his head. Shot! It falls a foot inside the rope at long-off
worked to a short midwicket
and it works immediately; short of a length, outside off and the batsman, wary of the keeper's position, remains in his crease but is beaten by the swing and Nixon collects
pushed to a wideish mid-off
massively wide. A filthy delivery which deserves to go for four and the batsman misses out, gets a bottom edge
a tighter line, but it's still wide of the off stump and causes a swing-and-a-miss from the batsman
just for variation, it's down the leg side this time
gone! What a soft dismissal. McCullum tried to hit it over Anderson's head but skied it to Vaughan at mid-off. The moment he hit it, McCullum swung his bat in frustration
oh and that's down the leg side
ooh very well bowled, swinging into the left-hander who didn't really come forward enough, but got an inside edge into his pad
defended out into the covers and Fleming's off the mark
hits him on the pad but it's going down leg
left alone outside off
again wide enough of the left-hander's off stump to leave alone
better; fuller and straighter and defended on the front foot
a touch fuller this time, again too wide and Fleming cracks it through the coers, albeit without sufficient timing. Calmly played
swing and a miss from Fleming. Neatly taken by Nixon
excellent ball, cutting back into Fleming who is quick to jab down on it
and an excellent delivery from Anderson this time, angling into Astle before cutting away off the pitch. Astle, stuck in the crease, fishes and misses
super line, that. Left alone with aplomb
Astle drives, with those concrete feet firmly stuck in the crease, and gets a thick outside edge past slip
wide enough for Fleming to leave it alone
down the leg side and Nixon shimmies to his left, taking the ball expertly. Still a wide, mind...
clunked on the front foot back to the bowler
ping! In the slot, on middle stump and Astle just lifts it over long-on for six. Easily eased
cor that's close. Astle leaves this on off stump and it misses his off stump by a whisker
left alone outside his off stump and Nixon fumbles it
a touch of away swing but it's again too wide
a touch straighter but wide enough to be left alone
on leg stump, Fleming tries to flick this over midwicket but misses out
down the leg side; have another wide
much better from Anderson - a fuller length, allowing the ball to swing, which it does, into Fleming's pads but it's down the leg side
on off stump this time - or middle-and-off - and Fleming defends
struck on the pad once more but it's drifting down the leg side once more
crashed straight into the pitch on the front foot, the ball bounces up high to Bell at cover who jumps up athletically to field
tries to drive this fluently, but with a closed face of the bat he rather mistimes it to midwicket
touch too short but Astle's cut finds point

terrible shot. Wide of the off stump, Astle tries to hit it over long-on - taking a step down the pitch. Had he connected with it, it might have landed back in New Zealand but he was several feet away from connecting
clunked into the covers off the back foot
this cuts back into Astle who plays it off the back foot
and again Flintoff jags this back into the right hander who is rapped on the pad
Fleming tries to flick this leg-side-drifter, misses; the ball hits his pad and flies to Nixon dives to his right and saves four. Terrific work there
jags back into Astle who is cramped for room and rapped on the pads
full and straight, going for the yorker and Astle digs it out to mid-on and they scamper a single
pitching on leg stump but swinging further down the leg side, preventing the umpire from raising his finger to Anderson's optimistic appeal
ah, lovely shot. Fleming's been looking for that shot several times; short of a length, he plays his customary pick-up-and-flick behind square on the leg side
too wide of the off stump, Fleming wisely ignores
and he leaves this alone to end the over
angling into Astle's pads who plays it into midwicket
too wide of Fleming's off stump for him to be bothered doing anything with it
that's a good length from Flintoff, but well defended off the back foot by Fleming
fuller and Fleming climbs into it, driving it with panache through cover - but not quite timing it as well as he might, and they pick up three
straighter, allowing a flick to the leg side
cracking ball, on the left-hander's off stump and it cuts away from Fleming's forward poke
shot! Clubbed down the ground, just over Anderson's head
Astle again refuses to move his feet, whacking this off the back foot to the right of Ian Bell at point who makes a fine sprawling stop
pushed off the back foot into the covers
nice length here (as much as an inanimate thing like "length" can be nice) and it's cautiously defended on the back foot
an ugly closed-face-of-the-bat sponge past the bowler and, oh dear, and Flintoff complete mistimes his dive at long-on! Spectacularly messy fielding there
goddim! Full and wide, a thick inside edge from Fleming who tried to drive that through the covers but failed to move his feet
nicely bowled, just outside off stump - quick, too, and it cuts back into Astle
but Astle responds with a fabulous four through extra cover, driving this on the up with perfect time
clunked to mid-off and they scamper a quick single
defended solidly on the front foot
very firmly worked to leg, with heavy bottom hand, but it's expertly stopped at short midwicket by the bloke whose name I can't quite see. Ah, it's Joyce
this spits up at Taylor who actually plays it very well, guiding it down to fine leg to retain the strike
outside the off stump and Taylor shuffles across, defending it with a flourish
again Taylor comes forward to defend with a very straight bat
a touch fuller and Taylor drives, confidently and with an impressive follow through, but straight to mid-off
gone! Anderson has three! Short, rising on Taylor who tries to pull it, but it rushes on him and he skies it to Michael Vaughan at cover
slower ball which is turned to midwicket
defended quite solidly on the front foot
too straight and it's nicely played, working this through midwicket
nicely defended off the back foot with the straightest of bats. Too wide from Flintoff
firmly defended once more off the back foot
a touch fuller this time and he comes forward to block it out on the front foot
too wide - fortunate not to be called a wide, too
tighter line but it's left alone
deliberately late-cut, I think, down to third man
excellent line and length and it's blocked out on the front foot
too straight and it's whipped with a nod to Des Haynes down to fine leg
opens the face of the bat, guiding this past point
bashed to mid-off
nicely bowled on middle stump, blocked out again
quick! That was fast from Flintoff, a good bouncer zinging over the batsman's head
88.9mph and it raps Astle's on the pad like a gangster rapper with gold bling dangling from his neck
terrific bowling! Fast, short, Astle thinks about hooking before snapping his neck and head out of the way
what a shot, what a fine shot indeed from Astle; a short-arm paddle behind square
too wide; called a wide
ooh Astle is rapped on the pad, half an appeal, and the ball races past Nixon for a couple of byes
left alone to end the over
excellent ball, on off stump and just swinging away a touch. But it's nicely played by the batsman, shuffling across and waiting for it on the back foot
smashed on the front foot, with immense power, and it falls a foot short of Flintoff - on the half-volley if you like - at mid-on. One of those nightmares for fielders
left alone outside off
on leg stump and worked through midwicket
pushed just wide of cover
lovely shot, just flicking this airily behind square
defended on the front foot
too straight, swept to fine leg
cracking ball! Just outside the off stump, turning away from the batsman's meek forward defence
defended on the front foot
on middle stump and it's blocked out
and it's defended to end the over
clunked into the covers
too short and it's worked through a bizarrely vacant midwicket
too short, too wide, but the batsman can't quite get hold it it, clubbing it cross-battedly through cover
nicely bowled from Collingwood; it's pushed back to him and he defends in his follow through
a touch of away swing, Fulton comes forward confidently and prods it into the covers
defended on the front foot to end the over
too short, cut past point
ah, lovely bowling. On off stump, turning away and the batsman comes forward
ooh and he tries to sweep but completely mistimes it
too short from Monty, Fulton goes back to defend
a quick single here as Fulton pings it past mid-off
"gorgeous, Monty" says Nixon to this one on off stump
clunked into the covers
defended on the front foot
ooh well bowled, cutting this back into the batsman who has to jab down on it
got him! Sent it wider of Astle, tempting him - perhaps the slower ball too - and Astle tried to smack it through the covers but got a thick inside edge
quicker ball to the new batsman who tried to leave it, but was stuck in two minds
defended to leg
on middle-and-off, turning away and it's defended
a touch shorter, clunked into the cover
shorter still - and slower, this time - timed off the back foot past point to bring New Zealand's hundred up
a touch too straight, on middle-and-leg, but the batsman plays it straight back down the pitch
half-a-shout to one which hits him on the pad
straight and worked to leg
swinging into the batsman who gets a thick outside edge, just wide of point who dives to field
that's better from Collingwood, forcing the defence from McMillan
swinging in again to the batsman who is cautiously forward, defending it very watchfully indeed
full and straight. McMillan still can't get this away
wide and McMillan slashes it over backward point. Fine shot and four
a slower ball which McMillan reads, can't digest and instead turns the page to enjoy the pictures
on off stump, Fulton is forward to defend albeit without much conviction
too straight, worked to leg
full and fast, pushed out to mid-off
again full, again quick and it's timed into the covers
stroked to long-off, neat stroke albeit without much power
and again they pick up a single into the covers
waits for this off the back foot, angling it to point
clunked to a wide mid-on
ooh, lovely bowling - a slower ball which just bends in the air slightly, but it's well defended by the batsman
nearly the fifth! Quicker this time and he gets an inside edge onto his left boot
defended on the front foot
another slower ball which foxes Fulton who plays it too early into the covers
neatly timed through midwicket with a flick of the wrists
too straight from Panesar and it's flicked quite nicely through midwicket
better line this time, on off stump and forcing the defence
ooh and he goes for a sweep, but can't time it
pushed out past point this time
defended on the front foot
a schwing and a miss and Nixon cries in anguish
again a false shot, trying to force it square but he's cramped for room and gets an inside edge which could so easily have removed his off stump
down the leg side and they steal a couple
outside off, the batsman stands tall and strokes it to mid-off but again can't find the gap
outside off and squirted to the bowlers left with a closed face of the bat. But no timing there
slower ball! Nicely bowled but it's defended on the front foot
oh and this is very well bowled; outside off, it spits up at the right-hander and evades the wicketkeeper
fine shot. That's broken the shackles at last for New Zealand, cutting it hard behind square
worked into the covers
too straight and it's nurdled through midwicket for a single
poor line, Fulton flicks it off his pads
so close! Outside off, Fulton drives, misses, and falls over...didn't move his feet
and Fulton goes for the big one here, lofting it over the infield but without much power and it falls safe
he comes forward and times it to mid-off, but without much poewr
neat stroke, cut late behind square and Dalrymple fields it expertly before slipping and allowing a single
full, wide, and timed past extra cover
and it's defended once again
gone! Two-metre-Peter tries to flick this over Michael Vaughan at short midwicket, but doesn't get enough height and it's well caught in the end by a jubilant England captain...his third catch today
wide of the left-handed Vettori who leaves it alone
fuller, tempting Vettori into a drive but he refuses to be lured and wisely leaves it alone
cut, quite expertly, very late, to a wideish gully
wide, and called a wide eventually, and Vettori went after it, trying to glance this past slip but missed
left alone once more outside off
just outside Vettori's off stump who defends off the back foot
on middle stump, worked to leg
cut off the back foot, but without much power
very neatly whipped off his legs, with an extravagant flick of his wrists, in front of square
and he's crashed this, very well timed indeed but just to Ian Bell's right at short extra, who fields very well
lovely late cut down to third man
a slower ball which Vettori times to third man
short, wide and square cut over the top - just over a sprawling gully - past third man for four
a touch fuller angling across Vettori again who late cuts
a stifled appeal as Flintoff raps McMillan on the pads. Bat first, though
cut down to third man, no great power in the stroke
struck on the pad, half a shout but it pitched outside leg
again angling across the left hander who times it down to third man
another slower ball from Collingwood but it's safely blocked out
full and straight - too full, in fact - and Vettori times it to long-off
swinging into McMillan who defends
pushed to mid-off, but there's no power in the shot
a touch shorter and it's cut hard to a deep point
pushed into the covers
full ball but Vettori misses his attempting flick to leg
dabbed down to short third man and the two batsmen scamper through
worked out through midwicket for a single, just working in ones at the moment, England will be quite happy about that

Monty makes the breakthrough with a full delivery which Vettori tries to sweep but is taken on the pad and umpire Rauf raises his finger. Vettori doesn't look happy and the replays suggest it could be drifting down leg.
onto the front foot and pushed into the gap at cover to open his account straight away
pushed down the ground to end a successful comeback over for Panesar and England right on top here. Not often we've been able to say that this winter.
comes forward and defends down the track back to Collingwood

GONE! another one bites the dust for New Zealand who are sliding into a deep hole. A full, drivable ball from Collingwood, but McMillan plays a fraction early and sends it straight back to the bowler or pouches a low catch in his follow through. Continues an excellent spell from Collingwood, whose medium pace is ideally suited to this surface
Bond offers the solid tailender's block to his first ball
same again from Bond, who can't afford to give his wicket away with so many overs left
slower ball from Collingwood and Bond plays and misses, but Collingwood isn't happy here and clearly has a problem with his leg or maybe the footholes
solid defence to a typical Collingwood delivery and that completes a wicket maiden as England continue to turn the screw
outside off stump and Franklin puts bat and pad together as the ball dribbles past silly point
pushed down to mid on and Franklin sets off, Bond is a little slow starting but makes it and Nixon can't take the throw cleanly meaning the pair get a second run. Little sloppy from England there
tickled off his pads and short fine-leg can't stop them getting another brace
nothing this time for Franklin as cover is quickly into to collect his forward push
half-hearted appeal from Monty, but he isn't going to get that one from Rauf as Franklin was well outside off stump
down the ground, comfortable run this time but nothing much happening for New Zealand in terms of runs
deflected down to third man, the standard one-day shot for a batsman just trying to rotate the strike
Bond can't connect with his attempted glide and Nixon collects
another slower ball from Collingwood and Bond just props forward
and again, Collingwood is really mixing up his pace well here - making the most of a slowish surface
another off-cutter and this times it takes a thick inside edge and runs out through square leg
another scoreless delivery is patted out towards point and Collingwood completes a fine 10-over spell, which has allowed Michael Vaughan to maintain control over New Zealand's scoring rate
turned towards square leg but there's man there to prevent the single
hint of turn into Franklin who defends and ball rolls down by his foot
Panesar keeping a tight off-stump line here as Franklin defends
same again, England could probably afford a couple of close catchers with Franklin purely in defensive mode
pushed out into the covers
flicked to midwicket, superb over from Panesar
tries a powerful sweep...but misses and the ball lobs into the off side for an extra
slightly on the legs but turned straight to short fine-leg
very full this time and Franklin places it well out to deep midwicket
and does the same again with some sharp running bringing another couple to the total.
glided to the captain at short third-man
connects with a sweep and Panesar does the cleaning up at deep square-leg
comes forward and back to the bowler
a rare poor ball from Panesar, who tries to fire in a quicker ball but it goes down the leg side and Nixon can't cover it. Fielder runs from short fine-leg to prevent a boundary
well bowled this time and Bond is beaten, the ball takes the pad and runs away for a couple
well bowled, hint of turn and Bond is beaten
batsman is beaten again as Panesar skips in his follow through at the excitement
thumped down to long off. That completes a fine spell from Panesar and he can he satisfied with his day's work so far - he'll be hoping he doesn't have to bat
starts with a full off-cutter

pushed into the covers, batsmen scamper a single, but the real drama is a limp from Michael Vaughan as he completes the fielding. Not a good sign for England, everyone is watching Vaughan's knee like a hawk
worked into the covers
Lewis continues with a tight line and all Bond can do is defend
cuts back into Bond, well bowled
full on middle and Bond squirts it out to midwicket but can't get a run
outside off stump and Franklin uses the extra pace on the ball to guide it past point
full pitched and a powerful drive, but straight to mid off
another one-day glide, bread-and-butter stuff
Flintoff hits 90mph (144kph) with this one and all Bond can do is quickly get into line and defend out to cover
the batsman again jumps into line as Flintoff hits that back-of-a-length area which is tough for the lower order
another back-foot defensive effort from Bond as Flintoff makes an on-target return
that's a chance, but a tough one as Franklin slaps the delivery back towards Lewis but all the bowler can do is stick up his right hand and deflect the ball past the umpire
that's what Bond needs to do, give the strike back to Franklin with a solid push
this time Franklin goes down the ground, still no boundaries coming
flashes hard at this one and it flies off the outside edge down to third man
thumps down the ground to Ian Bell at long off

bonus boundary for New Zealand as Bond picks the delivery well, a full ball, and plants it over mid off who is up in the circle. The Kiwis are still on for 200 here...which would be game on with an out-of-form Enland batting line-up
angled away to third man
few more shots appearing now as Bond swings hard at a near-yorker and the ball flies off the inside edge out to deep square-leg
short ball, off the bat onto the body and they scramble a single

GONE! important wicket by Flintoff as Franklin tries to go down the ground but doesn't get enough distance on the ball and Collingwood takes a safe catch at long-off. That's New Zealand's main chance of some late boundaries heading back to the shed
full, hint of movement into the batsmen who pushed into the covers to bring the new man, Mark Gillespie, onto strike
short from Flintoff, and quick, takes the shoulder of the bat but loops into empty space between point running in and Paul Nixon running forward...very close to a third wicket for Flintoff
outside off stump and Bond misses, decent pace from Anderson
lofted over Anderson's head but not timed and Bond loses the strike
heaved out through midwicket
a real tail-ender's swing this time as the ball flies out to deep midwicket, valuable runs

flurry of action as Bond plays an outrageous shot, tries to flick it over the keeper (like the Ryan Campbell ramp) but it flies down the third man and Monty Panesar slides like Jonty Rhodes to prevent a boundary. Great stuff all-round
down the ground
yorker, batsman backs away and the ball fires past leg stump
Gillespie not to keen on staying in line here, backs way and the ball takes his pad into the leg side
superb yorker, through to Nixon
short this time, good variety from Flintoff, and Bond swings and misses
connects this time, inside edge down to fine leg
another fine yorker to end Flintoff's spell, Bond manages to thump it down the ground but Flintoff will be happy with his efforts
carved through the covers, sweeper cleans up on the rope
yorker, Gillespie jabs down and completes a quick single
sharp running from this pair as Bond goes down the ground, long off does the fielding but can't get the ball back to Anderson fast enough
opens up his stance, but the effort was more dramatic than the result as the ball goes into the covers
very strange...Bond walks across the crease towards the off side and Anderson follows him, which means the ball is well wide of the stumps but as the batsman had walked across there's no wide
GONE! four for Anderson and a nice way finish. Gillespie, as he's done all innings, gives himself room but misses and the woodwork is rearranged

inn2.comm: on off stump Strauss blocks it out
lovely ball, angling into Strauss and straightening on him, just a touch. Strauss fends at it and misses
played off the back foot. Good length
pushed off the back foot into the covers
excellent start this from Franklin, not giving Strauss anything. Defended firmly
filthy pull - too short, too wide to be pulling and there was no conviction in that stroke from Strauss. An optimistic appeal from McCullum
pushed to leg, and he takes a quick single, sprinting hard...but he takes a long time to stop, running miles past the crease and clearly he's in trouble here
Strauss pulls inside the line here. Good ball on off stump
straighter, but too short and Strauss punches it off the back foot
on leg stump, pushed to square leg
lovely, elegant flick of the wrists to square leg. No great pace from Bond, Shane Bond, just yet
too wide, called a wide
and it's left alone by Vaughan to end the over
and Strauss comes down the pitch to this slightly shorter delivery, punching it back to Franklin
excellent ball cutting back into Strauss who, jumping back into his crease, defends
good ball in theory - the attempted yorker, looking to pluck out Strauss's leg stump - but he meets it on the half volley and flicks it past square leg for four
defended out to cover
a clunky, ugly and mistimed pull from Strauss
just short of a length and Vaughan immediately pulls this but just short of a straightish short midwicket
a little too wide of the off stump but Strauss's force off the back foot can't find the gap at cover
a 91.5mph (147kph) wide from Bond down the leg side
fine, elegant drive to extra cover. But straight to extra cover
very wide, tempting Strauss who buys into it and tries to smorgasbord it through cover but can only find fresh air
pushed down the ground. No run
defended on the front foot
a wide slower ball which is defended
oh, what a shot - what a beautiful cover drive from Vaughan. Enough said
he tries to repeat the same shot but it's fuller and he mistimes it
on leg stump and he rather misses out here
excellent ball, short of a length and forcing Vaughan onto the back foot
swing and a miss from Vaughan outside off
better, on leg stump and Vaughan tries to work it to leg but can't time it
quick, outside off and Strauss fishes and misses
outside off, Strauss defends it into the covers
and he late cuts this, very elegantly, down to third man
slower ball from Bond, Shane Bond, this time and Vaughan tucks it to leg for a quick (relatively speaking) single
ooh well bowled - fast, straight and smacked back to the bowler who stoops down to field
on middle stump and angling across the right hander who leaves it alone
he tries to work it to midwicket but mistimes it to mid-on
a neat flick of the wrists to this leg-side-drifter, picking up a single to square leg

Strauss takes a step down the pitch, trying to hammer it square but can't time it. Vaughan thinks there's a single, skipping down the pitch but has to turn quickly to make his ground....and struggles to do so.
pushed to cover
on leg stump and Strauss eyes runs here but his flick can't evade the short fine leg
ooh and Vaughan is struck on shoulder, a vicious bouncer from Bond, and the ball bobbles behind square on the off side. He takes a quickish single but really has to hurry to make his ground
pushed to cover
defended on the front foot - good line from Bond
hit hard, and elegantly on the front foot but Vaughan can't  find the gap at cover
just short of a length, Vaughan cuts it hard off the back foot
ooh and a very good ball outside off, Vaughan fishes and misses
Strauss again can't find the gap, cutting this to point
oh and he's timed this very nicely - but straight to short extra cover
so close! Strauss's concrete feet remain stuck in the crease to one which just cut back into him, and he gets a thick inside edge which just evades his off stump
a quick single to midwicket
short of a length and cutting back into him, Vaughan plays it off the back foot
blocked out on the back foot
well bowled, again cutting this back into the left hander who plays it late off the back foot
Strauss takes half a step down the pitch, hammering it hard but the off side is packed with fielders and he can't break the gap
cut late, neatly, but straight to one of the 400 fielders in the off side
driven to midwicket, Strauss wants a run but decides against it, and Dalrymple (the runner) quickly dives to make his ground
cut down to third man
cut off the back foot, but straight into the ground
short from Gillespie but Strauss doesn't connect with the ball, it lobs over the infield and falls short of the man in the deep
bowler oversteps this time and Vaughan comes forward, carefully, and defends down the pitch
too short from Gillespie and Vaughan rocks back and pulls sweetly through midwicket
covers up this time with a solid defensive effort as Gillespie pitches up more
well, maybe England are putting their foot down as Vaughan drives handsomely down the ground. Was a juicy half volley from Gillespite, but dispatched in style
opens the face and runs away to third man, Vaughan nearly forgets about his runner but the dodgy hamstring, or knee, reminds him
typical Strauss as he just milks a leg-stump offering into the on side. Easily England's best over, are they off and running?
glided very fine by Strauss, fine enough that the batsmen can make it back for a couple
straight from Franklin, worked to midwicket
on off stump, Strauss walks across a little and flicks it through square leg to the man on the fence
full and a handsome drive from Vaughan, but not quite timed and straight at mid off

GONE! That's the breakthrough for New Zealand and Vaughan's struggles are over. Short of a length and Vaughan goes for his favourite pull but doesn't really connect properly and slaps it straight to Ross Taylor at midwicket. Rather limp shot to be honest and he was clearly thinking about his leg problem, but New Zealand won't care they have their breakthrough
full on off stump and driven to mid off, safe start for Bell

forced off the back foot towards point and they sprint through for a single, Nathan Astle hits direct and Strauss makes it, although he didn't really ground run his bat properly like all school children are told
dabbed out to towards backward point
well bowled by Gillespie, squared Bell up a fraction - just as Glenn McGrath has done once or twice - but no slips and the outside edge brings two to third man...and it was no-ball anyway
goes back this time and punches to cover
bat and pad close together
very full, almost a yorker, Bell easily digs it out back to the bowler
full, searching for swing, and Strauss drives to cover
dabbed into where the slips would have been, Jeetan Patel comes round from backward point
outside off stump, Bell leaves well alone
back of a length and Bell tries to force this away but doesn't time it and the ball runs to mid off
too short this time, and a beautiful pick-up pull from Bell over square leg and away to the fence. Class.
follows the boundary with a leg-side nudge for one, keeps the scoreboard moving

another no ball from Gillespie, New Zealand's can't afford to gift extras, and it brings up England's 50 to not-so-massive applause from the crowd. In fact, it barely registers, all rather sleepy in Hobart
defend into the leg side this time
powerful square drive, well timed, but a brilliant dive from Jeetan Patel at backward point keeps it to two

CHANCE! big edge from Bell, low to McCullum's right and the keeper can't hang on. That's a big miss for New Zealand. Actually an easier chance that it first appeared and McCullum made a bit of hash of it really
on the pads and milked through midwicket, Bell takes a deep breath after his escape
solid, full face of the bat, and out to cover
punched into the covers
fuller this time and driven up to mid off

drifting onto middle and leg and flicked to short fine-leg, they go for a single and a direct hit would have been very close for Bell. Not sure who called there, should have been Bell as it went behind square
nudged backward of square on the off side
Strauss in typical nurdling mode, sends his out through point
driven firmly up to mid off
outside off, Strauss thinks about slashing it away but pulls out
driven firmly to mid off
short, but it's hard to time someone of Astle's pace and it goes to midwicket
again, short-arm jab out to midwicket
worked down to mid on, slightly strange to see that man back at this stage
played into the covers, good start from Astle, just what his captain wanted
uses his feet, still not a half volley, but Strauss crunches it away through the covers. Takes him past 2000 ODI runs, well done that man
comes half forward and produces a solid block

GOT 'IM! Slower ball from Franklin, Strauss tries to work to the on side gets a HUGE inside edge into his pad and Steve Davis raises his finger. Strauss can't believe it, just about sums up his tour, but it's another important wicket for New Zealand who have removed the man who was shaping to bat through the run chase
solidly behind his first ball
angled down to third man
another edge from Bell, this time wide of McCullum and no slips in. Flies away for a boundary but Bell living a charmed life.
hint of turn, played into the covers
very close for Joyce, tries to work into the leg side and gets a leading edge which falls into space just to the right of the pitch
better this time, driven to mid on
finally finds the middle of his bat, down to long off
Straighter one and Bell lets it go
punched down to long on, impressive start from Patel...how long until we see Daniel Vettori?
back of a length and a very straight bat from Bell down to mid off
driven again, but can't find a gap
tight lines from Franklin, not much to hit for Bell
played out to point
Bell playing this like a Test match, pushed out to cover
finally he finds the gap at cover, off the back foot but not timed perfectly and it pulls up before the rope. Bell keeps the strike
pushed into the off side
well picked up over midwicket, with the turn, but again not with timing and long on makes it round. Poor running only brings two
turned to midwicket
props forward, batsmen take off, backward point runs in and throws the ball to McCulluum but Joyce is home as the keeper takes out two stumps
all defence this time from Joyce, another tidy over
nice flight first up, played into the on side
fraction short this time and forced out to deep cover
beaten by the arm ball, very well bowled
Joyce finds the middle of the bat this time, but only to push the ball back to Vettori
deflected into the gap at point, nice use of the wrists - plenty of Graham Thorpe
played from the crease, tidy start from Vettori and England aren't exactly making a charge at this target
on leg stump but the flick doesn't beat short fine-leg
slightly quicker, Joyce plays a poor attempted dab and McCullum yelps in excitment
defends this time, not much intent here from Joyce. He said he wasn't going to copy KP and he's certainly living up to his word
covers up again
pushed out into the covers
Joyce manages to steal the strike with a push towards point, Fleming won't mind that
Nice flight, all the best of Vettori, and Joyce has to cancel any thoughts of an attacking shot
cleanly struck drive out to deep cover
pushed towards point

GONE! Pressure tells for New Zealand as Bell pushes towards point and sets off for a quick single, Jeetan Patel produces a direct hit from backward point. It was mighty close but the replays show Joyce's bat was on the line and that belongs to the fielders. It's breakthrough number three. Jitter time for England, New Zealand pumped and playing some fine, tight, cricket.
easily survives his first ball, comes forward with bat and pad together
nicely dabbed down to third man, good use of the wrists
comes forward, back to Patel
a rare New Zealand fumble, as Peter Fulton makes a mess of a regulation stop at short third-man
tucked to square leg
played square on the off side, easy run this time
Collingwood comes down the track, makes it into a near yorker and squirts it down the pitch
outside off, turning away from the right hander who goes back and pushes it out into the covers
"oooh super bowling Dan" cries McCullum as Vettori lands this on off stump and it's pushed back to the bowler
a skip down the pitch by Collingwood defending it
defended on the front foot
ooh, the arm ball from Vettori, beautifully bowled, and it passes by Collingwood's meek prod
on off stump, pushed to leg
flat and fast, hurrying the batsman who tries to turn it to leg but can't time it
Bell is itching to come down the pitch here, but doesn't, and prods it back to the bowler
a full toss which could have been slapped over extra cover. Or pulled over midwicket. Or even slogged over the top. Instead, he plays it back to Patel who dives to his right to field
clunked into the covers
and there's a maiden from Patel. Superb bowling
ooh close! Cut very by the batsman just past the lone slip, Vettori jumps up in anguish
nice flight this time from Vettori, but on the wrong line and it's easily worked behind square for a single
short and wide of Bell's off stump who rocks back and pushes it - without any power - into the covers
too short from Vettori, Collingwood turns him to leg
excellent length. Bell isn't sure whether to go forward or back - deciding on the latter
good length again, Bell comes forward, rightly so, and defends
down the pitch comes Collingwood...before defending it
flatter from Patel, a good line though, but Collingwood pushes it past him for a single
close! Very well bowled. Patel has been excellent today. Bell came down the pitch and played an indecisive check-drive which fell short of a deepish mid-off
worked through midwicket
lovely ball, lovely flight, just outside off and it's smothered by Collingwood
down the pitch from Collingwood who drives it with a straight bat down the ground
outside off, touch too wide from Vettori and it's defended
good intent from the batsman here, coming down the pitch and working it to leg
the wrong line from Vettori, firing it down the leg side. But still, Collingwood works it to leg with all the power of a one-armed frog and they only get a single
pushed out to short extra cover
cracking ball spinning past Collingwood's attempted cut
pushed out to point's right who runs across but can't prevent the single
another one of Collingwood's bizarre defensive shots, running down the pitch before blocking it out
gone! Great work from New Zealand. Collingwood again came down the pitch and, with an ugly, wasteful swish of the bat, slogged across the line and is caught at short midwicket
defended firmly on the front foot
flatter, outside off but Flintoff just pushes it out to cover
shot. Down on one knee and smashed over midwicket. Four. Easy.
brilliant bowling! Patel has been a joy to watch today. The arm ball which Flintoff doesn't read, spinning past his poking bat, and McCullum gets very, very excited
ooh and Patel nearly does Flintoff with a slower one but it lands just short of mid-on
just a single here as Flintoff nudges it to leg
very neatly played, cutting it behind square for one. Oh, no, overthrows here as it hits Flintoff's legs and they steal another
turned past square leg but just a single
flatter, speared into his off stump and it's blocked out
and it's nudged to leg for a single
slower, straighter and flatter, once more worked to leg
the wrong line from Patel and it's easily worked to leg
on leg stump, turned with a flick of the wrists by Flintoff but without power
ooh and he's thinking about it here, Flintoff comes down the pitch and threatens to hit it into the sea, before defending
and he comes forward, working it to leg. Excellent line from Patel once again
good flight, smothered by Flintoff
turns it behind square to retain the strike
too wide of the off stump, and no great pace from Bond, Shane Bond, there. Flintoff pushes it to cover and sprints for a single
ooh very well bowled from Bond! Bell tried to run this down to third man but missed - could so easily have go a thin edge
short and wide, an attempted slower ball, which Bell late-cuts down to third man
a reasonable bouncer which forces Flintoff to duck
Flintoff clangs this over midwicket here, without timing it, but such is his power that it dribbles over the boundary rope
a slower ball which Flintoff neatly pokes to cover and they scamper a well-run single
too wide of the off stump. Left alone.
shot! That's the way to do it. Patel just dropped it a touch too short and Flintoff, with massive power, heaved it over midwicket
ah, superb comeback from Patel; just a touch wider and fuller, turning back into Flintoff
Flintoff comes down the track again but defends
and he stays back in his crease this time, nurdling it late in front of square on the off side
very well placed from Bell, timed off the back foot to deep extra cover and they pick up two
late cut straight to the fielder at point
too quick for Flintoff who tried to pull Bond, but missed
good bouncer - well, a good length anyway - but it's too wide and Flintoff refuses to hook
and he drives but it's too short, and it passes by his inside edge
a neat, delicate guide down to third man
outside the off stump, excellent length and Bell just defends
quite well placed by Bell, just timing this off the back foot square of the wicket and Franklin, at fine-leg, jogs across but can't prevent two
defended on the back foot
down the track and a meaty blow to long on
neatly played off the back foot into the covers
Flintoff makes good use of the crease, backs away and makes room to go through the off side. Sweeper comes round but there's time for two
timed down to long on

GONE! That...is...massive. Bell goes back, plays all round a straight one from Patel and is trapped plumb. Asad Rauf raises the finger and it's another example of England's top order failing to build on a start. Huge pressure on Flintoff now.
defended on the front foot as Patel finishes a fine spell with his off spin. He's given New Zealand a real chance.
clubbed through the covers, not much timing but well placed
guided down to third man, now Nixon gets his chance
worked off his pads into the gap at midwicket
powerful cut through point, cover sweeper has to run round
very full slower ball, punched down to long on
on middle, worked just to the left of mid on and Nixon keeps the strike
tucked to square leg, well played
from the crease, out to point
rare bad ball from Vettori, too short and Flintoff thumps it through cover with such power that the sweeper can't reach it. See, scoring at a run-a-ball isn't that hard.
behind this slightly quicker one
ooh...Flintoff was thinking of going for a big one there but Vettori did him in the flight and Flintoff sensibly pulled out, turning to a safe block, and has a grin on his face
Nixon does the right thing again, plays down to third man and gets Flintoff back on strike
pushed to midwicket
tries a delicate glide to third man, misses it, and so does McCullum
straight to midwicket
down to third man, Leicestershire and Kent fans will have seen plenty of that shot over the years
driven to long on so Fred can keep the strike
pushed out to point, each dot ball vital for New Zealand
slightly squared up, back down the pitch
well time down to long off, but sharp work by the man on the fence keeps them to a single
moves over to off stump and pushes this into the gap at square leg
nearly...goes for a sweep and gets a top edge but it falls short of the deep square-leg.
hits the spot straight away and blocked
McMillan tumbles to the on side and fields the defensive push off his own bowling
again back to the bowler, pressure growing
and that pressure nearly tells as Flintoff tries to go over midwicket, doesn't quite connect, but the ball lands short of the man in the deep
a play and miss outside off stump
pushed to cover and an excellent first over from McMillan, it's nearly at a run-a-ball now
flicked through midwicket along the floor
tad short from Vettori, pulled out to deep square-leg
down to long on, just singles at the moment
picks out one of the men in the ring on the on side
down to long off
done by the slowness of the surface this time, think inside edge into the pads
back to the bowler
tries to break the shackles with his favourite shot over midwicket, doesn't get hold of it but falls safe
can't beat midwicket, New Zealand doing brilliantly here
pushed down to long off
he thought about going large, but instead opts to keep the strike with a single down the ground

Flintoff takes a chance and just gets away with it as the ball sails high down to deep midwicket where Ross Taylor gets his finger tips to hit but can't hold on and the ball drops a fraction inside the rope
off his pad, McCullum fields, Flintoff dives back
into the leg side
well placed to midwicket
another scampered single brings up a hardworking, and vital, fifty for Flintoff off 59 balls. Well played, but he has to see out the chase
back to the bowler and Vettori completes a tidy spell, although will be disappointed not to have a wicket on this surface
clubbed down the ground, on the up, to long-on and they run well for two
nicely played by Flintoff, using the pace of the ball and working it to leg
outside the off stump, Flintoff stands tall, massively, and clubs it back to the bowler
shot! That's what he was trying to do the previous delivery, just swatting across the line, in front of square, past deep midwicket
clunked through the clutch of seagulls for a single
excellent shot from Nixon, a flat, short-arm pull in front of square. Intelligent cricket this from England
hit back to the bowler
and the second dot ball of the over! An excellent line from Gillespie, no width whatsoever
ooh and Flintoff tries to swat this over long-on but skies it over the bowler's head, mistiming it. And it's a no-ball
well bowled, full and straight and Flintoff can only punch it for a single to mid-on
punched firmly to mid-off and they scamper a single. Scamper being the operative word...New Zealand's fielding hasn't been up to its usual sharpness today

gone! NO! Drama at Hobart! Flintoff tried to swat it over midwicket, skied it to Taylor at long-off. But Steve Davies, the square-leg umpire, adjudged that the delivery was above waist height and, as such, a no ball.
worked with heavy bottom hand through midwicket
fine, strong shot from Flintoff, picking this up off a length and it zings down the ground for four

ooh mistimed over cover, that's a poor stroke there but it nevertheless falls safe. They come back for two, oh dear, what's happening here? I think he's run out here! What a dreadful second run that was.
and he defends this on the front foot
crashes this into the covers
too wide and it's angled down to third man
but it's calmly pushed down to long on
excellent length and it's punched, or guided, to point
on off stump, Flintoff comes forward and punches it to the bowler's right for a single

that is some catch by Patel! Some catch indeed. Outside off, Dalrymple slashes at it to the left of Patel at point who dives, and takes it low, behind him. Superb and there's still a twist in this match!
ooh well bowled! Full and straight, Lewis's legs remain firmly concreted on his leg stump and he pokes this into the covers
nearly! Slashes it to Patel at point but it's just short
another dot ball! Again he gives himself room, swings, misses and flies through to McCullum
and it's slashed through the infield and, unbelievably, they take the single!
full toss, slashed to point once more...straight to point
and he clunks this to the leg side, to mid-on and they get a single
on leg stump, a little floater and Flintoff lifts it over the infield - and they pick up two! England cannot lose this match
bump ball! Hit back to McMillan
and Flintoff saves the day, driving this down the ground and England are up and running on their tour of Australia
